So, for `attr` and `operator[]` to be much nicer to use, we pretty much have to reimplement entire `handle` for it, this will result in a lot of copy/paste. The chances are, if you're reading an attribute / item, you will *always* cast it to `object`, since it's a pretty useless type otherwise.

I was thinking, why couldn't `accessor` just derive from `handle` (or even `object` actually), with the only difference being the overridden `operator=`? This way, `GetAttr` or `GetItem` would happen right away as you call the `attr` or `operator[]`. 

Also, why does the current code throw on a missing key / attribute when setting it, but not when getting it (e.g. in `operator object`?), instead silently setting `m_ptr` to `nullptr`? Wouldn't it make sense to throw in both cases for consistency purposes?

It would be also nice to be able to access `HasAttr` and `HasItem` in a more explicit way, e.g. by having `.hasattr()` and `.contains()` methods on `handle`.

A few hypothetical examples:

```cpp
// before
obj.attr("foo").cast<object>().attr("bar").cast<"object">();
// after
obj.attr("foo").attr("bar")();

// before
if (auto foo = obj.attr("foo"))
    foo.cast<object>();
// after
if (obj.hasattr("foo"))
    foo.attr("foo")();
// alternatively, if .attr() doesn't throw on missing attribute:
if (auto foo = obj.attr("foo")) // will have m_ptr = nullptr if missing
    foo();
```

Funnily enough, this wouldn't even break the current API much (worst case, you'll be casting object to object unnecessarily).

