@briandrennan

> I believe I understand what you're saying here, but just want to be sure I'm clear:

So I think you have the right high level idea, but the implementation here is a little subtle.  From the point of view of the engine, it doesn't understand anything special about closures and how to handle them.  Instead, it's something that the language host needs to handle.

If you'll indulged me, I'll give an overview of how this works in JavaScript land:

The relevant code is actually split across two places.  The first is the actual closure serialization code, which is [here](https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/blob/c2b2f3b117963bbddf869c483a4ee1e8d45475f7/sdk/nodejs/runtime/closure/serializeClosure.ts#L70.).  This code is responsible for actually taking a javascript closure and producing the source text that we'll register with lambda when we create the function.  The other half of the picture is in the pulumi-aws package itself, where we have a component resource called [`aws.serverless.Function`](https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi-aws/blob/567ee9d2d62c3a4116c13b6b67f2c782e7b38408/sdk/nodejs/serverless/function.ts#L101).  This component resource itself creates a bunch of sub-resources, one of which is the actual [`aws.lambda.Function`](https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi-aws/blob/567ee9d2d62c3a4116c13b6b67f2c782e7b38408/sdk/nodejs/lambda/function.ts#L13) that represents the physical AWS resource that backs the lambda.

The `aws.lambda.Function` resource has a property called "code" which is of type `pulumi.asset.Archive` which is basically a zip file, that contains both the code for the handler itself.

So the thing that flows from the language host to the engine is actually an archive that is suitable for uploading to lambda directly.

You can actually inspect the code that we end up including in the archive, by passing `--diff` to `pulumi preview` or `pulumi update`.

Consider the following small program:

```typescript
import * as aws from "@pulumi/aws";

const bucket = new aws.s3.Bucket("bucket");
const func = new aws.serverless.Function("function", {policies: [/* this should not be empty, but it is sufficent for running a preview */]}, (evt, ctx, cb) => {
    cb(undefined, `the bucket's id is ${bucket.id.get()}`);
});
```

If we run `pulumi preview --diff`, we see the following:

```
