            cb(undefined, `the bucket's id is ${bucket.id.get()}`);
        };
        
            }
          }).apply(undefined, undefined).apply(this, arguments);
        }
        
    }
}
```

The source text above is what was generated by serializeClosure.  You'll note that the start of the function is concerned with setting up the bucket object based on some state (in this case, since we are running a preview, some of this stuff shows up as undefined), and then eventually we jump into the user code (that's what `__f0` does).  The `__f0` function is exported from the module and we tell lambda to actually run. 

My belief for lambda with .NET is that we'll have to end up creating something similar, but instead of uploading source text, we'll actually have to upload a MSIL.  You can see in [this example](https://github.com/pulumi/examples/blob/176ce60f95128f42afae86281eb7098d399c3743/aws-ts-serverless-raw/index.ts#L53-L66) where we use a prebuilt .NET application to back the lambda.

So at a high level, that's what we'll need to do.  The serialization will end up needing to happen on the language side, because at the end of the day it needs to had the engine "here's a zip file with all of the code, and here's the fully qualified name of the function to execute".  In our case, that's going to be something Pulumi generates for you, I think.

> If this is the right approach, do you have any ideas about how you locate the correct class name via the reflection API? I've seen these in MSIL several times, but have never observed (or sought) a pattern for how the compiler names the classes.

I believe here we should be able to exploit the fact that `System.Delegate` is the top type for all lambdas and other delegates:

```c#
Func<string> myFunc = () => "hello-world";
Delegate myFuncAsDelegate = myFunc as Delegate;
Console.WriteLine($"Method is {myFuncAsDelegate.Method}");
Console.WriteLine($"Target is {myFuncAsDelegate.Target}");
Console.WriteLine($"Invoked is: {myFuncAsDelegate.Method.Invoke(myFuncAsDelegate.Target, Array.Empty<object>())}");
```

The "target" in the above is the display class that backs the lambda, so any closed over resources will end up being members on that class.  So I think closure serialization at a high level looks like, take the delegate, walk all the members on the display class and serialize them into some format that we choose (BinarySeralization, JSON?  Something else?).  If there are objects like Delegates, we'll have to apply this process recursively.  We'll also have to treat Resources as special during seralization. Then, produce a stub that, when invoked, re-hydrates everything and then invokes the delegate).  Include the MSIL for this stub with the uploaded program, and set it as our entry-point.

I realize the above is pretty hand-wavy and also probably sounds a little terrifying.  But I believe it should work.  I did some experiments back in march to at least prove out some of this, but I didn't take a run at the actual stub itself.

For what it's worth, we can put off delegate serialization for a long time and because the engine doesn't need to do anything special, in some ways this is just a gnarly dotnet thing, but it doesn't have any intrinsic ties to Pulumi.  ike, it sucks because you don't get the nice lambda behavior, but it's not the end of the world.  Indeed, we have not tackled this problem for either Golang or Python today and we've still be able to do a lot of cool things.

Anyway, sorry for the long post.  But I wanted to give you an idea of how both the system works and where my head is at for some of this stuff.

AWS accepts a zip file with jar inside lib folder, so this is the workaround I'm using now:
```
    code: new pulumi.asset.AssetArchive({
        "lib/lambda-java-example-1.0-SNAPSHOT.jar": new pulumi.asset.FileAsset("./java/target/lambda-java-example-1.0-SNAPSHOT.jar"),
    }),
```

